<HEADLINE>
<P>
LETTERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * "The Power, Pleasures of the Pen" (Column One, April 3) really caught my 
eye. I agree with Jerry Lee Hill, "There is nothing that can take the place of 
a letter." 
</P>
<P>
 Being a pack rat who resists discarding personal letters, I have special notes 
going back 50 years . . . or more. I call them my "treasured possessions." They 
stir up memories to make me laugh, or cry, remembering the joys or sorrows of 
life. 
</P>
<P>
 When my son left home for Alaska in 1973 he answered our letter to him with a 
quote: "Like cold water to a weary soul is good news from a distant land" 
(Proverbs 25:25). 
</P>
<P>
 Everybody loves to get a letter. Thanks for giving us new insight in "The 
Power, Pleasures of the Pen." 
</P>
<P>
 DARLENE KEPPLER 
</P>
<P>
 Torrance 
</P>
</TEXT>
