<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFF THE TICKER: BRITS IN MIDDLE OF GUMMY MESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Things have gotten sticky as two U.S. companies battle for big shares of 
Britain's chewing gum market.After Warner Lambert complained that sales 
representatives from Wrigley were removing display cases of Dentyne and Clorets 
from stores, the government obtained assurances from Wrigley that the practice 
would stop. 
</P>
<P>
 Wrigley controls 88% of the British market but has seen Warner Lambert chewing 
up a bigger piece of the action recently. Warner Lambert has the other 12%, 
about double the company's market share of five years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA041994-0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 033554 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
April 19, 1994, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 2; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
133 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: BANKING & FINANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 T-Bill Rates Hit Two-Year High: Interest rates on short-term Treasury 
securities rose in auction to the highest levels in more than two years. The 
Treasury Department sold $11.8 billion in three-month bills at an average 
discount rate of 3.76%, up from 3.63% last week.Another $11.8 billion was sold 
in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 4.21%, up from 4.03%. The 
rate for three-month bills was the highest since they sold for 3.95% on April 
6, 1992. The six-month bill's rate was the highest since it averaged 4.27% on 
March 23, 1992. The new discount rates understate the actual return to 
investors: 3.85% for three-month bills, with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,905, 
and 4.36% for a six-month bill selling for $9,787.20. T-Bill Auction 
</P>
<P>
 3-month: 3.76% 
</P>
<P>
 6-month: 4.21% 
</P>
