<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: CAMARILLO; COMMISSION TO STUDY DEVELOPER'S REQUEST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By J. E. MITCHELL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Members of the Camarillo Planning Commission tonight will consider a request 
by Pardee Construction Co. to build 160 condominiums and 42 single-family homes 
on a 19-acre parcel on the city's east side. 
</P>
<P>
 Staff members are recommending approval of the homes to be located near 
Mission Oaks Boulevard and Woodcreek Road. 
</P>
<P>
 But Matthew Boden, city director of planning and community development, said 
he also has concerns about excess noise from Mission Oaks Boulevard for homes 
on four lots. 
</P>
<P>
 Boden said staff is recommending that the commission ask Pardee to construct a 
wall and redesign some driveway entrances from Mission Oaks to help dampen 
noise. 
</P>
<P>
 The project must still be approved by the City Council because it has fewer 
homes than first planned. 
</P>
<P>
 Pardee Project Manager Bill Teller said the company opted to go with a lighter 
density development because of the surrounding neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
 "We just felt a less dense development worked better with the characteristics 
of that particular neighborhood," he said. "It's really a better fit." 
</P>
<P>
 The Planning Commission will meet at 7:30 p.m. at City Hall, 601 Carmen Drive. 
J. E. MITCHELL 
</P>
</TEXT>
