<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE PEOPLE'S PLAZA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Thousand Oaks theater commission has considered banning heavy metal and 
rap music concerts from the new Arts Plaza out of concerns over attracting 
"hordes of sometimes rowdy teen-agers." 
</P>
<P>
 Any rendition of Ravel's "Bolero" brings to mind, among other things, the 
vision of Dudley Moore scrambling to engage in out-of-wedlock sex with Bo Derek 
in the movie "10." 
</P>
<P>
 Can the commissioners envision the day when overzealous fundamentalists 
petition them to ban classical music because of how it can inspire some to 
engage in demonic fornication? 
</P>
<P>
 Get with it. This is America. That teen-agers are not yet old enough to 
protect themselves via the voting booth does not give the commission the 
authority to suggest which form of artistic expression should grace their 
precious "elegant concert hall" and which should not. The hall belongs to the 
city, therefore, the people. 
</P>
<P>
 BRUCE ROLAND 
</P>
<P>
 Ojai 
</P>
