<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: WILSHIRE DISTRICT; 
COUNTRY CLUB SETTLES DISCRIMINATION SUIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Wilshire Country Club reached a confidential settlement in a lawsuit 
brought by a former employee who claimed that the club discriminated against 
black workers, the woman's attorney said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 As a condition of the settlement, the amount was kept confidential, said 
attorney Dan Stormer, who represents Margaret Inyama. 
</P>
<P>
 The plaintiff, who was a cook at the club, claimed that the discrimination 
included forcing black employees to park in separate parking lots from whites.  
</P>
<P>
 The 52-year-old Baldwin Hills resident also claimed that she was physically 
abused by her boss, who allegedly pushed her against the side door of a walk-in 
freezer so hard that she had to get medical treatment.  
</P>
<P>
 Inyama, who was on a disability leave when the suit was filed, has been unable 
to return to work because of complications unrelated to the lawsuit, Stormer 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
