<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: HEALTH CARE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by James M. Gomez, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Smelling Thin: Ron Nicklaw has a nose for news. 
</P>
<P>
 The Huntington Beach distributor for Nutrition for Life, a provider of 
weight-loss products, said he is hoping to cash in on a brand-new product that 
he said is revolutionary. 
</P>
<P>
 The product is called the Thin Pen, a pocket-sized device that Nicklaw said 
will pare unwanted pounds off people who simply stick it in their noses and 
take a sniff. 
</P>
<P>
 That's right. You just sniff the pen and watch your weight go down, Nicklaw 
says. 
</P>
<P>
 The Thin Pen takes advantage of a recently completed study by a Chicago doctor 
who discovered that people who smelled certain aromas right before eating had a 
smaller appetite. 
</P>
<P>
 Dr. Alan Hirsch found that, of the 3,000 people he subjected to a variety of 
smells, such as green apple, banana and peppermint, he noticed average weight 
losses of five pounds. 
</P>
<P>
 Nicklaw said he is beginning to market the three-set Thin Pens, which cost 
$31.95 for the apple, banana and peppermints scents, through the local 
newspapers and mail-order ads. 
</P>
<P>
 "I was skeptical at first," Nicklaw said. "But I had a chance to study it, and 
it looks real interesting." 
</P>
</TEXT>
