<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTH AFRICA: A TALE OF SIX FAMILIES; SOUTH AFRICA: FORGING A NATION; FAMILY 
PORTRAIT / THE MOFOKENGS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL PARKS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Shirley, 51, manager at a clothing factory 
</P>
<P>
 Patience, 30, organizer for a retail trade union 
</P>
<P>
 Churchill, 28, teacher 
</P>
<P>
 Audrey, 21, unemployed 
</P>
<P>
 Nathan, 17, student 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Home: Soweto 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Politics: Member of the African National Congress 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Background: Shirley's parents were born in Johannesburg of parents who had 
migrated from rural areas. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Shirley Mofokeng: "The ANC will need much time to turn things around -- three 
to five years for changes to become visible -- and people will have to be 
patient, though they won't like it. If we are not steadfast on the course we 
set, we could ruin the new South Africa." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA041994-0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 033742 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
April 19, 1994, Tuesday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Page 4 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
