<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHARLES R. TAYLOR; BAPTIST MINISTER HEARD ON TV, RADIO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Charles R. Taylor, 79, Baptist minister heard on television and radio 
specializing in Bible prophecy. Taylor was born in Zion, Ill., and educated at 
the religion-oriented Wheaton College in Illinois.For more than four decades, 
Taylor was based in Orange County, where he published Bible Prophecy News and 
conducted a radio and television ministry. Until precluded by illness about a 
year ago, he appeared weekly on the Tustin-based Trinity Broadcasting Network 
telecast to stations across the country. Taylor continued his radio sermons 
until recently. One of his best-known followers was Rollen Frederick Stewart, 
who became known as "Rainbow Man" for wearing multicolored wigs and T-shirts 
imprinted with Bible verses and for flashing religious placards at televised 
sports events. Taylor, who defended Stewart as well-meaning and harmless in his 
various brushes with the law, baptized Stewart when both traveled to Israel in 
1981. On Friday in Anaheim of cancer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
